flowRoot.flowPara: Report on findings relating to the prediction of AFL results during game

Prediction of AFL game results is an interesting and ever present idea in Australian Culture, and has been for all of it's history. This poster analyses how game results can be predited as the game plays.

The aim of this research was to find how well the winner of a game could be predicted before the game finished, but while it was being played. The data desired initially was just the probability that the leading team at any given quarter was the winner of the final game, but this expanded into wondering whether this probability changes per team and per year, and the margin teams were winning by.
As a game goes on, it will become ever more certain that the leading team will win the game.

When the probability of the leading team at a quarter winning the game is ploted, the hypothesis that certainty will increase over time will increase is verified as being true. The leader by the 'fourth quarter' is always the winner, which makes sense, as the winner is by definition the leader at the fourth quarter. The winner of a game is highly likely to be the leader of the third quarter.

Due to the scale of the data (every AFL game ever recorded) a script was written by a team member to scrape the data avaliable online into a database to be analysed further by a secondary script. This script was written by this team member in Node JS and is avaliable online at __________.

The data avaliable online was verified from various sources. The sample size was counted by the script to be over 16000 games analysed, giving highly accurate results. The scripts results were manually checked for a number of seperate years and tested well. We believe this data is highly precise.

flowRoot.flowPara: Report on findings relating to the prediction of AFL game results.

The prediction of AFL game results is conducted by both professionals and football fans in Australian Culture, and is a large part of Australian history. This poster analyses how game results can be statistically analysed to predict game results as they are being played.

The aim of this research was to find how well the winner of a game could be predicted as the game was being played. This prompted the research into whethor the winning team of past games was winning at each quarter, and on average, by how much. This was extended by researching whethor this had changed over football's history, and whethor it varied between grand finals and typical games.
As a game goes on, it will become ever more certain that the leading team will win the game.

When the probability of the leading team at a quarter winning the game is ploted, the hypothesis that probability will increase over time is verified as being true. The leader by the 'fourth quarter' is always the winner, which makes sense, as the winner is by definition the leader at the fourth quarter. The winner of a game is highly likely to be the leader of the third quarter.

Due to the scale of the data (every AFL game ever recorded) a script was created by a team member to scrape the data avaliable online into a database that could be further analysed by a secondary script. This script was written by the team member in Node JS and is avaliable online at __________.

The data avaliable online was verified from various websites. The sample size was counted by the script to be over 16000 games analysed, giving highly accurate results. The scripts results were manually checked for a number of seperate years and tested correct. Being a perfect machine, we believe this data is highly precise.

tspan.tspan: Average margin that winning team is winning by per quarter

flowRoot.flowPara: This graph depicts the average margin by which the winning team of a game is winning by per quarter. This data includes quarters in which the winning team was behind the leading team, pushing averages down. As it is clear, by the end of the game, the leading team is typically beating the losing team by a significant score.

When these graphs are viewed together, it can be said that as a football match progresses, the winning team typically excels in front of the losing team, and the losing team has a lower chance of making a comeback. This could be because losing by a lot is harder to catch up on than losing by a small margin.

Between the years of 1900 - 1970, the average probability the third quarter leader won the game was 84%. This is has increased to 87% percent for the years 1976 to 2016. Between the years of 1900 - 1970, the average margin the winning team was leading by in the third quarter was 19.84. This has since increased to 26.88 for the years 1976 to 2016 (+8.68 points). This increase in both likelyhood of third quarter leader winning and third quarter margin could be due to rule and player development, or could simply be a random difference in scores.
Analysis could have been improved by extraploting trends in data, and placing games per game on a graph.
'All Games' is all games in rounds or grandfinals in the years 1900-2016 that were not draws or other special exceptions.
